node.title: Gauge Invariance
node.bodyText:
Hi there,
I am wondering how MOOSE handles gauge invariance. When solving a set of problems that has gauge variance should the user select a predefined gauge to work within, or will gauge invariance be handled by the test function?
And subsequently, should the user define a gauge, will this affect the results/convergence of the kernels due to some interaction with the test function?
This might be one that @cticenhour might know the answer to.
Any help would be much appreciated!
Many thanks,
Gillian

We don't currently have a model example that applies a gauge and solves for a vector potential in the MOOSE electromagnetics module, as Maxwell's equations are manipulated into coupled wave equations and solved directly for the electric and magnetic vector fields. Adding a Coulomb gauge, in particular, is something that is on my roadmap for the coming months of development for a research project, but isn't ready yet.
The gauge invariance isn't handled by the test function. We use a first-order Nedelec vector basis from libMesh for most problems, and the recent introduction of Raviart-Thomas elements in libMesh is something I also want to explore. So, if you wanted to attempt to define a gauge in your problem, the test function should not affect the results or convergence (at least in a way specific to the gauge, I believe). @lindsayad or @roystgnr may be able to give some insight on the libMesh test functions and correct me if I am wrong here.

Ok great, thank you very much for the help!
I will keep an eye out for the addition of a Coulomb gauge, and I will impose my own gauge for now.
All the best,
Gillian
Without spending too much time re-learning gauge invariance, I would need to see the PDEs you want to solve

Disclaimer: I know basically nothing about gauge invariance.  It might be wise to stop reading this comment after that sentence.
Is the idea here that we're solving for a divergence-free vector field like the magnetic field B, and ∇·B=0 implies that there exists a potential-vector field A such that B=∇×A, so we'd like to be able to just solve for A directly and get a strongly divergence-free B, but the problem is that A is only unique up to some transformation (like adding ∇Ω for some smooth Ω) that changes A but not B?
If you're solving a problem like that in 2D, you can use a variable defined with one of the libMesh C¹ scalar-valued elements (CLOUGH works on general grids; HERMITE is more efficient if you have a cartesian mesh), treat its values as if they were magnitudes of a vector field in the z direction, take the curl of that field to get a divergence-free vector field in the xy plane, and the kernel of that operation is just the constant fields so you can add a single extra residual term to pin the value at one point to get a well-defined potential.
If you're solving a problem like that in 3D, you could still use three HERMITE variables to give you components of a C¹ vector field, and take the curl of that to get a divergence-free 3D vector field ... but now the kernel isn't a simple one-dimensional thing, it's dimensionality is something like a third of your degrees of freedom.  Maybe there's some efficient way to constrain that and keep going, but when I looked at that problem during my PhD I was advised to find something easier instead.

node.title: Questions about InterfaceKernels/BCs System- implementing custom interface conditions

node.bodyText:
Just considering heat conduction, when you integrate your weak form by parts, you end up with a surface term:
<test, n * -k * grad T>
where n is the surface normal. If an interface kernel implements the residual:
<test, conductance * (T - T_neighbor)>
then it is weakly setting the condition:
n * -k * grad T = conductance * (T - T_neighbor)

I see. So it is able to find out that info based on what I define in the kernels? That, and I assume the BC system does the same thing, i.e uses <test, n * -k * grad T> to apply the Neumann BCs?
Then how could a case where the discontinuities are not related by the flux be implemented? For this case, what if , instead of q_var + C*(T_var - T_neighbor) = 0, you had C*(T_var - T_neighbor) + CONSTANT = 0?
I'm asking because in my case, q and T are both independent variables weakly related through kernels I implemented. So for my interface condition, I would like to use Coupleable to couple the values of q and T at both "var" and "neighbor var", and then implement my custom interface condition.
Also, is there a way to extract the unit normal at a surface in MOOSE? I would need to multiply q by the unit normal. With the unit normal I should be able to find a unit tangent as well.

So it is able to find out that info based on what I define in the kernels? That, and I assume the BC system does the same thing, i.e uses <test, n * -k * grad T> to apply the Neumann BCs?

The code isn't finding out anything. It's just how the numerics of the finite element scheme workout. You have to write out your weak form and identify what terms have been integrated by parts. Often it is only the diffusion or conduction portion of the equation, in which case your surface term is <test, n * -k * grad T>. If you don't apply any boundary condition or interface kernel, then you are weakly setting n * -k * grad T = 0. If you write one BC with residual <test, A>, another boundary condition with residual <test, B>, then you will be weakly setting n * -k * grad T = A + B

Then how could a case where the discontinuities are not related by the flux be implemented? For this case, what if , instead of q_var + C*(T_var - T_neighbor) = 0, you had C*(T_var - T_neighbor) + CONSTANT = 0?

Hopefully you have at least some term that is integrated by parts? You could implement this condition using a penalty method (or in theory a Lagrange multiplier but that takes some more work). You could write a residual that is <test, penalty * (C * (T - Tn) - CONSTANT)>. The larger the penalty factor the more closely you would require your condition to be met. Note that this will still weakly enforce a condition: flux = penalty * (C * (T - Tn) - CONSTANT)

I'm asking because in my case, q and T are both independent variables weakly related through kernels I implemented. So for my interface condition, I would like to use Coupleable to couple the values of q and T at both "var" and "neighbor var", and then implement my custom interface condition.

If my answers to the above questions don't help, then we can talk more about this.

Also, is there a way to extract the unit normal at a surface in MOOSE?

Yes, it is _normals[_qp]

What I meant by "finding out" is, is MOOSE able to automatically know what the BC term looks like based on the kernel term, since they both come from a term that was integrated by parts?

I wouldn't say MOOSE automatically knows; I would say "the math" automatically knows. There is nothing in the code that draws a relationship between kernels and boundary conditions.

In the case where nothing was integrated by parts (and hence, no grad_test kernel term), how does MOOSE know what the Neumann condition should be like?

If no term is integrated by parts, then it does not make sense mathematically to impose an IntegratedBC or an InterfaceKernel. You would be imposing a boundary or interface flux that should not exist

As for the implementation of the custom interface condition, if I use a kernel with a penalty, since it involves two variables that are defined only on separate blocks, will MOOSE only try to implement it at the interface where both variables are defined? I don't want it to try to force that condition within the bulk of the two blocks, only at the interface.

Interface kernels only run on the boundary you assign them. Unlike "regular" kernels they are boundary restricted as opposed to block restricted.

I was also thinking about strongly enforcing the condition by creating a material file where I use coupleable to couple the needed variables, do the calculations, and then output a material that I can apply as a dirichlet condition for each q variable on either side of the boundary.

Imposing Dirichlet conditions at interfaces degrades the accuracy of the finite element method. I would avoid that if possible.

This is an implicit expression for q, will it be able to handle that? i.e a BC that basically depends on the variable itself? Getting it explicitly as a function of q would be hard, but easier to do explicitly as a function of each of the T's.

All residual objects in MOOSE whether Kernels, IntegratedBCs, NodalBCs (DirichletBCs), or InterfaceKernels fully support implicit treatments. This is the "bread-and-butter" of MOOSE

I saw in the documentation that I can define "boundary" for material files. Will that ensure that the custom values (that become the dirichlet condition) are only calculated on that boundary?

Yes, those material calculations will be restricted to that boundary.

Since the condition only applies to the normal component of my q variables, I will need to define an aux variable which is the projection of q on the unit normal to do that. I was thinking of outputting the unit normal at each qp as a material, and then doing the dot product calculation in the "expression" field for the AuxKernel. Can BCs be defined for Aux Variables?

This is becoming quite the chain. If you are using an IntegratedBC or InterfaceKernel you could use the _normals member that already exists. As a NodalBC this would be pretty difficult. You cannot use a material property in an aux kernel that runs on nodes. Similarly you could not use an elemental variable or a material property directly in a NodalBC.

For any of this to work, can I define boundary conditions that depend on a variable? That is, the variables coupled within my material file used to calculate the BC.

You can use any kind of variable in an IntegratedBC or InterfaceKernel. You can only use C0 family variables (e.g. Lagrange) in NodalBCs
This is helpful thanks! I'm going to try to implement first and see how that goes.

Just wanted to provide an update on this, I added a comment to #25894 regarding an issue faced with my attempt, i.e using the method of implementing the interface condition as dirichlet BCs.

As for using the InterfaceCondition or IntegratedBC, I'm not sure how that would work here noting:

Note that this will still weakly enforce a condition: flux = penalty * (C * (T - Tn) - CONSTANT)

and I don't have anything to do with the flux here, as I am implementing each T and each component of each q as independent variables (i.e taking this to 8 equations instead of 4).
Also, I am taking the variation of A3b and A1b wrt q, but doing that for A1b means there is no flux term.

Actually, since the integrated BCs

weakly enforce a condition: flux = penalty * (C * (T - Tn) - CONSTANT)

would it make sense to provide flux = flux + penalty * (C * (T - Tn) - Expression)
i.e basically hardcoding the BC term there so that as it forces it to equate to itself, the expression has to go to zero? If so I can try to redo the whole thing and take the variation of A1a and A3a wrt to q so I can have flux terms for each. Only issue is that I'll have to deal with the second gradients in A3b but I think MOOSE has a coupledSecond.

So it seems to me you are using a mixed formulation, with both the temperature and flux as nonlinear variables. Have you looked into Raviart-Thomas finite elements? @nmnobre how are we doing on getting RT into MOOSE? Is it ready?

Yes exactly that. I am not sure how else I would implement otherwise as getting A3b explicitly in terms of q seems like an impossible task, not to mention the interface normal condition (A6).
I have not heard of Raviart-Thomas finite elements before, how would they work in this case?

Almost. I was refactoring last week, and I think I left it at a stage where it compiles and it should work unless I messed up any signs in the kernels, https://github.com/farscape-project/moose/tree/rt. I can have a look on Monday. It's still missing documentation too. The plan was to get those TET14s merged beforehand and since that (and RT) both depend on an up-to-date libMesh I slacked a bit and worked on other stuff. :/
In other words, it's probably in a state where it can be used, not in a state where it can be merged.

node.bodyText:
Hello,
I started exploring the SIMP omptimization capabilities of MOOSE recently and noticed that the SensitivityFilter only partially behaves the way I'd expect it to or rather how I'm used to. It does prevent checkerboarding and introduces a minimum length scale dependent on the filter radius - as expected. However the boundaries are way clearer than I'd anticipate. For reference, here are two pictures from an optimization with similar setup from ABAQUS and MOOSE with a filter radius of 10 times the element size:


The clearer boundaries from the MOOSE result are instantly noticeable. A straight 0-1-design is considered a good thing, I was just wondering how exactly the MOOSE SensitivityFilter works since I recon it differs from the standard sensitivity filter used here for example. I'm primarily having a hard time understanding the functionality of RadialAverage and the meaning of _JxW[gp]. Maybe the resulting MOOSE filter is one of the ones mentioned here in section 5.2?
Thanks in advance.

There are multiple sensitivity filter forms with different pros and cons. When using the Radial Average Sensitivity filter, the current psuedo density is not used in the calculation, but is used in the paper you provided. There is no "correct" filter since this is mostly a heuristic used to alleviate checkerboarding and have minimum length scale.

Thanks for your answer. I failed to think about the absence of the density in the MOOSE filter.
I'm aware there is not one correct sensitivity filter as the second paper I linked suggests. If one aims to replicate a similar filter to the one used in the widely known 88 line Matlab code they can use a ParsedMaterial for the numerator which is passed to RadialAverage in conjunction with a slight modification to the denominator in SensitivityFilter (dividing by the pseudo density of the current element). See 2d_mbb_sens_filter.i in my simp repo for reference.
[filter_mat]
    type = ParsedMaterial
    property_name = filter_mat
    material_property_names = 'sensitivity'
    coupled_variables = 'mat_den'
    expression = 'sensitivity*mat_den'
  []
Very cool, do you have a picture by chance using your method?

Sure!
Standard MOOSE filter method

Modified MOOSE filter

Matlab 88 line code result

Please note that the modified MOOSE filter is not exactly the same since I haven't figured out how to pass the weight (or rather a weight_sum) variable from ThreadedRadialAverageLoop.C to SensitivityFilter.C yet. So that is still missing in the denominator of the filter.
